Why do you want to be on SAAC, and what do you hope to accomplish through being a representative?17 responses
I want to be on SAAC to help have a positive influence on campus and on the community. I also want to step up as a leader and help represent the student-athlete body among campus and the community. Through being a representative, I'm hoping to make improvements on campus for the student-athletes and I hope to help make a positive impact on the Babson campus and the surrounding community.
My primary mission in joining SAAC is to become the change I want to see in the athletics program here at Babson. As a black male and one of the only black men in my sport, I experience a lot of microaggressions that I feel need to be corrected on behalf of the entire athletics department. My unique perspective by way of my background is what I believe I will contribute to SAAC. In my tenure as a member of SAAC, I want to give insight into how to make a more diverse athletics program here at babson. Being a black athlete here, and one of few, I believe that Babson can do a better job in recruiting people who look like me, and I want to help bring that bolster in diversity which I know Babson is capable of achieving.
I want to be on SAAC because it is the heart of athletics. It allows student-athletes to have a voice on campus and during important decisions. I also want to meet like-minded leaders on campus who want to make a positive impact.
I want to be on SAAC because I want to take a leadership role within athletics off the field. I believe I have some great ideas to improve the athlete culture on campus, and can also make a difference in planning and executing events, community service, and social media campaigns. I also hope to work behind the scenes in sports some day, and SAAC would be a fantastic learning experience on how athletic communities operate behind the scenes, and how much effort it takes to create change. I believe that I will provide great input in meetings, and will be able to bring suggestions from all student athletes to the table. I hope to create relationships with other student-athlete leaders on the Babson campus as well.
I want to be on SAAC because I think having a group of students like this is very important. We all want to be able to make change and to be able to be leaders for our team and for athletics. I hope to help lead out transition from this COVID season to our next steps. In our current state there are issues that teams are running into. I hope to be a voice that will help to lead athletics in a positive direction. I want to help to get things at Babson to the way they were before this pandemic. This will require hard work and patience that I think that I have.
My desire to be a part of SAAC is rooted in having seen such impactful and vital influences on our Athletics community from current members of SAAC. Whether the aforementioned members were my own teammates or leaders from fellow teams, I wish to strive to catalyze a similar and equally necessary impact. I hope to be an essential aspect of shaping the life of student-athletes at Babson and throughout division III Athletics, through supporting the promotion of equity, autonomy, and positivity.
I am hoping to become more educated on social issues in the athletics perspective and be able to educate fellow student athletes
I want to be on SAAC to be apart of a community that shares similar goals and faces similar challenges with academics and athletics. Through being a representative on SAAC I hope to bring student-athletes at Babson together as well as support to surrounding athletic communities
I want to become more involved in representing my teammates as well as other student-athletes at Babson. I want to be able to listen to their voices and opinions and make sure they are heard by SAAC and athletic administration when necessary.
I want to be a SAAC representative because of my want to contribute to the need of representation for the student athlete population.
I want to be one of the voice's of the men's basketball team and represent our values. My goal is to represent EVERYONE on the team and make sure opinions are voiced.
I did the SAAC takeover one day and I really enjoyed it. I think giving the student athletes a voice is very powerful and I want to be a part of the force behind it. I dont think there is any representation from the womens basketball team and I would love to be a source of communication. Having a season during the pandemic has showed me how much goes in to producing something we all love to do. With new ways and solutions during an unprecedented time, I believe student athlete voices need to be heard now more than ever. This involves issues such as mental health and safety protocols for student athletes. I believe I have great ideas and Id love to be a part of something that could present them to those who make decisions.
I want to be on SAAC because I believe that the success of student athletes at Babson will resonate through the entire college and uplift the whole institution. I hope to be able to create an image of athletics at Babson as an expression of how talented Babson students are.
I want to bring student athlete mental health into to a better light because it is often looked over. I also would really love to get teams involved in the One Love organization which is a organization that promotes education and awareness about health relationships. It involves many educational workshops as well as fundraising opportunities.
I hope to be able to successfully represent and support my teammates and fellow student athletes. I want to be a voice that works for the benefit and well-being of all. I also hope to be able to strengthen my leadership skills, all while meeting new people. I hope to engage in actions of change and unity. I want to be a helping hand and one that others can reach out to in case of any concern.
I want to be on SAAC because I want my teammates and I, as well as all other student- athletes at Babson to have access to representatives that can make their comments or concerns be heard with people who can actually change policies or agendas to better reflect their wishes. I hope to make people more comfortable with airing their issues or constructive comments by having more team discussions to open the dialogue between teams and their representatives.
I want to be on SAAC because I saw first hand how much of an impact having a voice for my teammates and other student athlete peers could have on our combined experience. We were even able to present ideas to the conference and NCAA as a whole. As a representative I would love to increase our community outreach as an athletics division and find new innovative ways to do so even during the pandemic.

Describe three of your strengths that you can bring to this position.17 responses
One strength I have that I can bring to this position is that I am very personable. I get along with others very well and I am able to get along with and work with many different kinds of people. Another strength I have that I can bring to this position is that I am very well spoken. I have no issue speaking in front of others or in front of large groups of people and I feel I have the ability to express my thoughts clearly and concisely. A third strength that I believe I can bring to this position is that I am very passionate. When I get invested in something, especially something that I care greatly about, I do my best to put in extra effort and devote time and energy into doing a good job.
As a proven student leader here at Babson college by way of my experience as a freshman delegate in the Multicultural Student Leadership Council and as an elected Freshman Senator I have developed three critical strengths to make me an effective leader. My first strength that I will bring as a member of SAAC is my outgoing nature. Being outgoing in respect to being a leader means to always speak up about any and every thing. As a student leader here, I have spoken up against the lack of diversity here at Babson, by working closely with deans and faculty to create real change here at babson. My next strength I will bring to this position is my curiosity as a leader. My curiosity as a leader is what pushes me to ask the challenging questions to help create the change we need to see. My curiosity as a leader prompted me to question why Babson athletics has not posted anything about balck history month and as a result I have begun working closely with Mike Lynch to help create real change within the athletics program. My third strength that I will bring to this position is my charisma. As a leader here at Babson I have learned that the more positivity I exert into my community, the better the community around me is. I want to bring a positive aura to SAAC that will allow meetings to be more interactive, an aura that will make events funner, and an it factor that will make the athletics program better overall.
natural leader, people oriented, hard working
1. Ambition: My ambition drives me to want to be the best, and do the best I can in every position I am put in. I will push my hardest to make every SAAC initiative successful, and try to create a big presence across campus. My ambition to turn athletics at Babson into a culture across the entire student body will be reflected in my work on the committee. 2. Kindness: I like to say that I am an empathetic and kind person. I treat everyone around me with respect, and listen to what others have to say no matter what. I understand that being a part of a committee like this, people will disagree on certain matters. Being able to handle these situations in a kind and civil matter is important. I can also empathize with other student athletes, and will try to make their experience better and listen to their problems and suggestions. 3. Creativity: I love to think of new events, activities, and campaigns. I am able to create and adapt under pressure, and understand the emotions and desires of students across campus, which will help me plan and execute events and activities more effectively and with a great response. I am not afraid to present different ideas, and to take a leadership role doing these things.
I think one of the strengths I bring is that I am a team player. I believe that I am someone that is easy to work with and will do whatever is necessary to help us all succeed. I am someone that knows their role and will stick to it. I think another strength I have is that I am motivated. In high school I was a 3 sport captain in addition to being a leader of 2 clubs while keeping my grades very high. I think that when I get my mind to something I can accomplish it. I always try to do my best work and will work to make sure it is always up to best and highest standard. I think that one final strength I have is that I am open minded. I think that in a role like this you need to think about the greater good and cant think about just yourself. You have to be able to make sure you hear everyones opinions and feelings on issues. I think that I am very good at listening and keeping my thoughts open before I make a decision. I try to stay as open as possible instead of just doing things that make me happy.
I believe that my ability to both lead and be an excellent teammate will be essential in my success in SAAC. I understand the importance of having a strong and guiding voice in certain situations, while also being a supporter in converse scenarios. Additionally, I believe that my presentation and speaking skills will be imperative when conveying nuanced ideas and larger themes that are being discussed. Furthermore, my creativity is also an extremely essential skill that I possess. I am high experienced in graphic design, photography, videography, drawing, and writing. These creative skills, in conjunction with my strong creative ability to generate new and relevant ideas, would be imperative to the success of my role in SAAC.
Creativity, positivity, and determination
Support, Leadership, Creativity
I have strong leadership, organizational, and communications skills that I believe will help me be successful as a representative of student-athletes here at Babson.
Experience with over wellbeing (both mental and physical health) from being a pow. Leadership; whether its being a role player or needed leader for an event my past experience in the classroom, professional, and athletic setting have equipped me to succeed. My network across the Babson community has been created from having friends from various team. I believe in the importance of athletes not being divided or solely identified as an athlete in their sport. They are so much more.
strong morals, good intentions, kind spirit
To start, I love conversing with people and collecting feedback. Having listening skills allows me to hear the concerns of others and make sure they feel acknowledged. Also I am a very creative and solution based person. This allows me to not only listen to the concerns of others but come up with potential ideas for change. Lastly, I am able to communicate my own thoughts and ideas as well as voice the concerns of others. With the combination of listening, creativity, and communication I believe I would bring many useful skills for this position.
I am organized, empathetic, and logical
I am a great leader. I have leadership experience as I was a 3 sport captain in high school as well as Vice President of my high school class. I am organized and I love to push myself to better myself as well as the others around me.
Compassion, determined, reliable
Positivity, team-oriented, and open-minded
Three strengths that I can bring to this position are my leadership abilities, decisiveness, and experience. These three combined allow me to openly communicate, efficiently work in a group setting, and successfully contribute as a member of SAAC.

What are three ways SAAC can have a more visible presence on campus?17 responses
I think one way SAAC can have a more visible presence on campus is having some sort of information session or event during freshmen orientation for the student athletes. I think making the new student athletes aware of SAAC and giving them information about it could be key to growing the group. Another way SAAC could have a more visible presence is hosting some kind of event on campus which would make the group and the members more visible. A third way SAAC can have a more visible presence on campus is recruiting more student-athletes to join. I think that the more members there are, the more that the group will be able to spread across campus and the more information can be passed along between peers.
The first thing SAAC can do to make a more visible presence on campus is to have more widespread events, more specifically an intro event such as a What is SAAC event. As a freshman on campus, I haven't heard too much about SAAC, and I feel like if they had larger events I would know more about SAAC as a student athlete. Another way SAAC could have a larger presence on campus is by having campus ambassadors. If there was a dedicated task force to promote the presence of SAAC on campus, then at that rate more people would know about SAAC. One last thing SAAC could do to increase their presence on campus is to physically talk to students on a larger scale. If there was a practice where we spent the first 15 minutes learning about SAAC, from that point forward the organization would have a more visible and known presence amongst all student athletes on campus.
more eye catching instagram posts/ stories (take overs, cute posts, etc), doing an event (food truck), posters
-Send out weekly video updates made by SAAC members for the student-athlete community to watch. -Create a "theme of the month" with events, speakers, and resources surrounding it, and promote it to the student body. -Create a better fan experience to attract more people to games such as food tents, canteens, tailgates, lawn games, competitions at half-time for fans, etc, (when COVID is over).
I think that one way SAAC can be more visible on campus is too have events. I think that right now in COVID it is thought but being able to help events to engage students could be a way to get our name out more. I think having some sort of mentorship program for freshman could be useful. The jump from high school to college in both athletics and academics is huge. I think SAAC having some sort of mentorship program would be very helpful for mental health as well. Lastly I think SAAC could have time where members on a specific could have a forum for their team. This could allow an open decision about what needs to be changes and how we can do it. I think that working together as a unit would be a great idea. Making all of the athletes feel like that are heard is something that should be a priority.
I believe that Babsons SAAC has an extraordinarily strong and positive reputation on the Babson campus, and I believe there is even more that we can accomplish to promote it to an even higher level. Through an expansion of social media platforms, we can reach a more diversified range of student-Athletes. This could be seen through creating a tiktok, snapchat, and engaging in collaborations with preexisting Babson Athletics accounts. Further, I think that SAAC could host more events on campus to further engage and connect the community as a whole. What does it mean to be a student-athlete at Babson?17 responses
To be a student-athlete at Babson means striving for excellence academically, athletically, and personally. With the academic difficulty at Babson, managing athletics and academics is a challenge that Babson student-athletes willingly undertake to benefit themselves in the future. Also, with a high level of competition, Babson student-athletes push themselves to improve in their sport and as teammates and leaders. Being a Babson student-athlete also means trying to be a better version of yourself on a daily basis. This includes having a positive impact on others and improving your ability to work with and be around peers and teammates.
Being a student athlete at Babson means to hold yourself to an admirable standard of excellence. In my eyes, an admirable standard of excellence encompasses being an inspiration to non-student athletes on campus. Embodying a standard of excellence would prompt other non student athletes to question things like How does Demarre do it? How does demarre balance sports with clubs and keep a good gpa? The striving for excellence in everyday endeavors as student athlete is what it means to be a student athlete. It's one thing to be an athlete, but to achieve excellence in the classroom and in your extracurriculars, is what establishes an admirable standard of excellence for others, that's what it means to be a student athlete at Babson.
It means being a leader on campus. We are all more than the title we wear; it is how we represent our school, our schools' name, and the surrounding community. Babson athletics is something I am proud to be a part of. I feel that the student-athletes here are all striving for success in and out of the classroom.
Being a student-athlete at Babson means representing your school on and off the field, and putting your best foot forward in all aspects of your Babson life. Personally, being a student-athlete provides me with an identity on campus, and the ability to instantly make connections with other student-athletes as well. Competing at a high level at Babson requires commitment, passion, perseverance, balance, and a drive to succeed in every way. Being a student-athlete has helped me to achieve my goals in the classroom as well by providing me with support, friendships, mentorship, and an outlet to blow off steam and have fun. I could not imagine my life without being a student-athlete at Babson, and I hope to make the experience better for everyone.

We are the images and perception that the school gets throughout the NEWMAC and throughout the New England area. Babson is providing me the opportunity to live out a childhood dream of being a college athlete. They have given me the chances and the tools to be able to compete at the highest level and across some of the best competition the Northeast has to offer.
Being a student-athlete at Babson is more than being a student and more than being an athlete. It transcends scoring highly on exams and throwing no-hitters. Being a Babson student-athlete, implies within itself, that you are consciously making an effort to progress as a human. It means that you choose to be cognizant about your place in the world, and make deliberate choices to lead with empathy, strength, and resilience. It is a privilege that should not be taken lightly, as well as an experience that is unfathomably unique and infinitely valuable.
At Babson, specifically, means being blessed enough to continue to play the sport we love at a competitive level while studying at an institution that challenges us academically to prepare us for the real world
Being a student athlete at Babson means being apart of an inclusive community that values academics, athletics and service. Being a student-athlete at Babson, I am able to balance the responsibilities of both academic and athletics. At all times I acknowledge I am representing Babson and try to conduct myself in a way that my teammates and classmates would look up to. I prioritize all-around health and wellness first (which student-athletes sometimes neglect), then academics, then athletics.
Being a student-athlete at Babson is a privilege, not a right. It's more than the countless hours of training, working out, and studying. Being a student-athlete gives us the opportunity to wear Babson's name on the front of our jerseys and represent the school both on and off the field. It also allows us to create long-lasting friendships and bonds with our teammates and other student-athletes within the community.
Utilizing ET&A to excel in the classroom and in your sport. I know that may be cringy but its true. Babson students have a different mindset that allows them to be great leaders.
Someone who values a team environment at an academically rigorous school

What have you gotten out of your collegiate athletic experience so far?17 responses
So far in my collegiate athletic experience, I have met some of my best friends and I have had the opportunity to learn from some of the smartest and most hardworking people about what it takes to be a successful athlete and a successful person. I have learned lessons and skills that I can apply to my sport and other lessons that I can apply to my daily life to be a better person, student, or friend. These lessons have been invaluable and I don't think I would have had the opportunity to learn some of these lessons with college athletics.
Thus far the biggest thing I have gotten out of my collegiate athletic experience are not the tangible or measurable things like a new personal record or stronger bench press , but a priceless commodity: mindset. Thus far at Babson, becoming a collegiate student athlete has proved to be one the hardest things ive ever done due to the time commitment and dedication it requires. It's hard to gain the discipline to eat right throughout the day, it takes grit to study past midnight after a 4 hour practice, it takes dedication to consistently workout on a daily basis. These challenging tasks have given me a stronger mentality to complete these long days, finish all my assignments, and even study at the most inconvenient hours. This mindset fostered thus far because of my collegiate athletic experience is what will propel me into my future as an entrepreneur.
I have learned that not everything comes easy, and hard work is essential for receiving results. I have also come to know that the community we have built is the main reason for team success. People in athletics all lean on one another for support, whether it be surrounding mental health issues, physical roadblocks, academics, or personal reasons. I have learned to be a leader and a friend being on Babson Swim and Dive. I have taken in the freshman this year, which has helped me grow as a leader tremendously. I am always there, making sure they are doing okay and balancing things well with our "season" and Covid.
My athlete experience has confirmed that Babson was the right place for me to go. I have made countless friends, overcome many mental and physical challenges, created lasting athletic, academic and social memories, and become more confident to be involved on campus and approach new people. Being a Babson athlete has provided me with something to compete for, and a drive to be better everyday. My Babson experience would not be the same without the athletes surrounding me.
So far my experience has been very positive. I think that in these times Babson has done a lot to support athletics. There are other schools that are just canceling teams seasons without any sort of explanation. Babson is giving all of us an opportunity to compete even in the times of uncertainty. I think this shows the level of commitment that Babson has towards athletics and it makes me excited for my future. This season seems to be a preview of great things to come. The school is doing their very best to give me a chance and that is something I really appreciate.
My collegiate athletic experience has taken a path unlike many individuals prior to me. Having my freshman season canceled unexpectedly in the blink of an eye was a unequivocally devastating experience. One that I will carry with me forever. However, it is not the trauma and melancholy that I will live with, but rather the newfound appreciation I found for my sport. Covid revitalized not only my appreciation for softball, but appreciation for the presence of sports, teammates, and competition in my own life, and that of my teammates and fellow athletes. I have extracted so many valuable lessons about being a teammate and leading through my actions. Being an athlete has always been very special to me, but being an athlete for Babson is something that has redefined that notion within my life.
I am blessed for the family and community I have been able to build not only with my team but with fellow student-athletes
My collegiate athletic experience so far has brought me a team environment at practice and hopefully we will compete this spring at matches, where I am able to forget about the craziness of the world outside sports and the stress of academics. My athletic experience has taught me lessons I will use outside of sports, such as showing up on time, how to interact with others from different cultures, and most importantly how to be a supportive teammate. Being apart of a team at Babson has allowed me to make friendships and connections that will last long after graduation.
Being a collegiate athlete has given me friendships that will last a lifetime, as well as helped develop my leadership, time-management, and teamwork skills, among many others, that I will be able to tap into even after my soccer career comes to an end.
Understanding of what I truly love (to run). The importance of commitment. How to be an effective leader. And most importantly, life long friends.
Improved social and leadership skills, expanded my network, and broaden my comfort zone as a leader
Having my only season during the pandemic has taught me a lot about athletes here at Babson. The winter athletic teams such as men's basketball, women's basketball, and hockey showed tremendous leadership and strength while carrying out a season during all the madness of COVID-19. I noticed more than I think I would have with a regular season of how much it means to be able to step on the court. I have learned that collegiate athletics is a very precious thing that cannot be taken for granted because you never know when it can all stop. I want to take my opportunity as a student athlete at Babson and make the most of it. This involves a high level of engagement and support for my community. Overall from my condensed season I learned that athletics and playing is something so engrained and precious in the lives of our students that the continuation of it is vital not only for social reasons but more importantly mental health.
A sense of community and relationships that are bound by shared struggles/experiences.
Being that my first two collegiate seasons have been affected greatly by COVID, Ive really been able to focus on relationships off the field with my teammates. The relationships Ive been able to build with girls both older and younger than me are very special and something that has truly shaped my college experience. Ive gotten to see how special relationships with teammates are and how important they are to team success.
Out of my collegiate athletic experience, I have gotten life-long friends, unforgettable experiences, and the most amazing memories. Going out to the Babson field every day is a gift and something I deeply cherish and value. I have never been a part of a more inspiring program.
The past two years have taught me a lot about being flexible, especially with competing during the pandemic. Not only have I had to keep an open mind when it came to different practice times, pods or virtual competition, it allowed me to have a more positive mindset regards college during covid in general.
I have gained an immense pride in myself and being a part of a team from my student athlete experience. I have been blessed with the most fulfilling bonds with my teammates and friendships that will last a long time. My collegiate athletic experience has pushed me into leadership roles and allowed me to find my voice and confidence, both of which can be used to accomplish my goals outside of athletics.

2021-2022 Student-Athlete Advisory Committee (SAAC) Application
Deadline to Apply is March 24, 2021.

The Student-Athlete Advisory Committee (SAAC) is a committee made up of student-athletes dedicated to protecting student-athlete welfare, fostering a positive image of the athletic community, and providing leadership opportunities beyond their sport. SAAC reps. specialize in focus areas including Community Service, Community Engagement, Diversity & Inclusion, Health and Wellness, Mental Health, and Special Olympics. Babson Athletics is looking to select members of each varsity athletic team to fulfill the roles and responsibilities of serving this committee.

Selection Criteria:
Members are selected based on their interest in serving on the committee; willingness to be an active and engaged participant; experience working with student organizations; and availability to participate through the 2021-2022 academic year.
